  "text": "The JVM bytecode interpreter dispatch loop in OpenJDK is implemented through a template-based system that generates platform-specific assembly code at runtime. The main components are:\n\n1. **Core Interpreter Framework**: The TemplateInterpreter class (src/hotspot/share/interpreter/templateInterpreter.hpp/cpp) manages the dispatch tables and entry points. It maintains multiple dispatch tables: _active_table (currently used), _normal_table (normal execution), and _safept_table (safepoint mode).\n\n2. **Bytecode Dispatch Table**: The DispatchTable class provides a 2D array indexed by TosState (Top-of-Stack state) and bytecode value. Each entry contains the address of the corresponding bytecode handler. These tables are accessed via dispatch_table() and related methods.\n\n3. **Method Entry Points**: The EntryPoint class wraps entry addresses for different TosState values. Entry points are generated for method invocations, returns, exception handling, and deoptimization.\n\n4. **Interpreter Code Generation**: TemplateInterpreterGenerator (src/hotspot/share/interpreter/templateInterpreterGenerator.hpp/cpp) generates all interpreter code. The key function generate_all() sets up:\n   - Return entry points (via generate_return_entry_for)\n   - Invoke return entry points\n   - Result handlers for native calls\n   - Safepoint entry points\n   - Exception handlers\n   - Method entry points (normal, native, intrinsic)\n   - Bytecode entry points via set_entry_points_for_all_bytes()\n\n5. **Bytecode Templates**: TemplateTable (src/hotspot/share/interpreter/templateTable.hpp/cpp) defines templates for each bytecode. Each Template specifies properties (bytecode, TosState input/output, whether it dispatches) and a generator function.\n\n6. **Bytecode-to-Bytecode Dispatch**: The generate_and_dispatch() function is the core of the dispatch loop. It:\n   - Executes template-generated code for the current bytecode\n   - Increments the bytecode pointer (bcp)\n   - Looks up the next bytecode in the dispatch table\n   - Jumps to the handler via the dispatch mechanism\n\n7. **Architecture-Specific Dispatch**: Each CPU architecture implements dispatch via InterpreterMacroAssembler (src/hotspot/cpu/[arch]/interp_masm_[arch].cpp/hpp):\n   - dispatch_prolog: Prepares for bytecode execution\n   - dispatch_epilog/dispatch_next: Executes the actual dispatch\n   - dispatch_base: Core dispatch logic that loads bytecode, indexes into dispatch table, and jumps\n   \n   X86 (src/hotspot/cpu/x86/interp_masm_x86.cpp) uses: lea + jmp with direct table address indexing\n   ARM/AArch64 use similar patterns with architecture-appropriate instructions\n\n8. **Safe Points and Polling**: The dispatch mechanism includes safepoint polling checks to allow JVM to pause threads when needed. The safepoint table provides dispatch addresses that check polling words.\n\nAll architectures (x86, x86_64, aarch64, arm, ppc, riscv, s390) implement this pattern with architecture-specific code generation in templateInterpreterGenerator_[arch].cpp and dispatch logic in interp_masm_[arch].cpp. The zero interpreter provides a C++ fallback implementation."
